Cohort Creation

On Pembrolizumab

# Search for pembrolizumab in standardized terminology table
filtered_pembrolizumab <- standardized_terminology[grepl("pembrolizumab", standardized_terminology$code_description, ignore.case = TRUE), ]

# Filter Medication Ingredient Table using pembrolizumab codes
pembrolizumab_medication_ingredient <- medication_ingredient |>
  filter(code %in% filtered_pembrolizumab$code)

# Filter Procedure Table using pembrolizumab codes
pembrolizumab_procedure <- procedure |>
  filter(code %in% filtered_pembrolizumab$code)

When you filter for the pembrolizumab code (1547545) in the medication ingredient table, you get a cohort of 536 distinct patients. When you filter for pemrolizumab code (J9271) in the procedure table, you get a cohort of 493 distinct patients on pembrolizumab. Among the 43 patients with pembrolizumab records only in medication_ingredient.csv, all of them had chemotherapy record and had their pembrolizumab use date within 7 days of a system-recorded chemotherapy line. This temporal overlap strongly suggests that pembrolizumab was part of the chemotherapy regimen, despite the absence of a corresponding J-code (J9271) in procedure.csv. So we will use the cohort including 536 patients.

# Filter patient table to only patients on pembrolizumab medication ingredient
patient_cohort <- patient |>
  filter(patient_id %in% pembrolizumab_medication_ingredient$patient_id)


# Filter the medication_ingredient table to only patients who are on pembrolizumab (but include all their rows of medications)
medication_ingredient_cohort <- medication_ingredient |>
  filter(patient_id %in% patient_cohort$patient_id)

Earliest Start Date Record of Pembro (For Each Patient)

# Step 1: Rename columns to have the same name for consistency
proc_df <- pembrolizumab_procedure %>%
  select(patient_id, date) %>%
  rename(event_date = date)

med_df <- pembrolizumab_medication_ingredient %>%
  select(patient_id, start_date) %>%
  rename(event_date = start_date)

# Step 2: Combine both data frames
combined_df <- bind_rows(proc_df, med_df)

# Step 3: Order by patient_id and event_date
combined_df <- combined_df %>%
  arrange(patient_id, event_date)

# Step 4: Assign a sequential date index per patient
combined_df <- combined_df %>%
  group_by(patient_id) %>%
  mutate(date_index = row_number()) %>%
  ungroup()

# Step 5: Pivot wider to spread the dates across columns
pivoted_df <- combined_df %>%
  pivot_wider(
    id_cols = patient_id,
    names_from = date_index,
    values_from = event_date,
    names_prefix = "date_"
  ) 

# Step 6: Join the BC_diagnosis_date column
final_df <- diagnosis_BC_earliest %>%
  select(patient_id, BC_diagnosis_date) %>%
  left_join(pivoted_df, by = "patient_id")

Join BC_diagnosis_date and pembro_initiation to patient_cohort_flagged:

pembro_initiation = first pembro record after BC_diagnosis_date

# Create the flagged cohort
patient_cohort_flagged <- patient_cohort %>%
  # Step 1: Join BC diagnosis date from final_df
  left_join(final_df %>% select(patient_id, BC_diagnosis_date), by = "patient_id") %>%
  
  # Step 2: Join first post-diagnosis pembro date
  left_join(
    final_df %>%
      pivot_longer(
        cols = starts_with("date_"),
        names_to = "date_index",
        values_to = "event_date"
      ) %>%
      filter(!is.na(event_date)) %>%
      # First join BC diagnosis to this temp table BEFORE filtering
      left_join(
        final_df %>% select(patient_id, BC_diagnosis_date),
        by = "patient_id"
      ) %>%
      filter(event_date > BC_diagnosis_date.x) %>%
      group_by(patient_id) %>%
      slice_min(event_date, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
      ungroup() %>%
      select(patient_id, pembro_initiation = event_date),
    by = "patient_id"
  )

Add Metformin Indicator and Dates to patient_cohort_flagged

# Join all data into patient cohort and clean up non-metformin users
patient_cohort_flagged <- patient_cohort_flagged %>%
  left_join(metformin_dates, by = "patient_id") %>%
  mutate(
    metformin = if_else(patient_id %in% metformin_flagged$patient_id, 1, 0),
    metformin_start_date = if_else(metformin == 1, metformin_start_date, as.Date(NA)),
    metformin_end_date = if_else(metformin == 1, metformin_end_date, as.Date(NA))
  )

Surgery (yes/no)

surgery_cpt <- procedure %>%
  filter(code_system == "CPT") %>%
  mutate(code_chr = as.character(code),
         code_num = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(code_chr))) %>%
  filter(
    code_chr == "19499" |                     # Unlisted breast procedure
    between(code_num, 19301, 19307) |         # lumpectomy/mastectomy
    between(code_num, 19340, 19342) |         # implant insertion
    between(code_num, 19361, 19369) |         # autologous reconstruction
    code_num %in% c(19328, 19357) |           # implant removal / expander
    between(code_num, 38500, 38525) |         # LN biopsy/excision
    between(code_num, 38740, 38745)           # axillary dissection
  ) %>%
  select(-code_num)


surgery_icd10pcs <- procedure %>%
  filter(code_system == "ICD-10-PCS") %>%
  filter(
    str_detect(code, "^0H[BTRUXHWP]") |   # Breast roots
    str_detect(code, "^07[BTC]")          # Lymphatic roots
  )

surgery_icd9cm <- procedure %>%
  filter(code_system == "ICD-9-CM") %>%
  mutate(code_num = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(code))) %>%
  filter(
    between(code_num, 85.20, 85.23) |   # partial excision/biopsy
    between(code_num, 85.33, 85.36) |   # simple mastectomy
    between(code_num, 85.41, 85.48) |   # modified/radical mastectomy
    between(code_num, 85.50, 85.54) |   # reconstruction
    between(code_num, 85.60, 85.67) |   # implant/expander ops
    between(code_num, 40.23, 40.24) |   # LN biopsy
    between(code_num, 40.50, 40.54) |   # regional LN dissection
    code_num == 40.19                    # other LN excision (incl. axillary)
  ) %>%
  select(-code_num)

surgery_code <- bind_rows(
  surgery_cpt %>% mutate(source = "CPT"),
  surgery_icd10pcs %>% mutate(source = "ICD-10-PCS"),
  surgery_icd9cm %>% mutate(source = "ICD-9-CM")
) %>%

  mutate(
    date = as.Date(date),
    code = as.character(code),
    code_system = as.character(code_system)
  ) %>%
  distinct(patient_id, date, code_system, code, .keep_all = TRUE)


surgery_with_pembro <- surgery_code %>%
  left_join(
    patient_cohort_flagged %>%
      transmute(patient_id, pembro_initiation = as.Date(pembro_initiation)),
    by = "patient_id"
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(pembro_initiation), !is.na(date), date <= pembro_initiation %m+% months(6))

surgery_prior <- surgery_with_pembro %>%
  group_by(patient_id) %>%
  summarise(surgery_prior_date = min(date), .groups = "drop")

patient_cohort_flagged <- patient_cohort_flagged %>%
  left_join(surgery_prior, by = "patient_id") %>%
  mutate(surgery = if_else(!is.na(surgery_prior_date), "yes", "no"))

# Medication classes and their drugs
drug_classes <- list(
  Biguanides = c("metformin"),
  Sulfonylureas = c("glimepiride", "glipizide"),
  Meglitinides = c("nateglinide", "repaglinide"),
  TZDs = c("pioglitazone"),
  Alpha_glucosidase_inhibitors = c("acarbose", "migitol"),
  DPP_4_inhibitors = c("alogliptin", "linagliptin", "saxagliptin", "sitagliptin"),
  Bile_acid_sequestrants = c("colesevelam"),
  Dopamine_2_agonists = c("bromocriptine"),
  SGLT_2_inhibitors = c("canagliflozin", "dapagliflozin", "empagliflozin", "ertugliflozin"),
  Amylin = c("pramlintide"),
  GLP_1_receptor_agonists = c("dulaglutide", "exenatide", "liraglutide", "lixisenatide", "semaglutide"),
  Insulin_GLP_1_receptor_agonists = c("glargine", "degludec","detemir")
)

# Function to filter standardized terminology for a given drug name
get_filtered_codes <- function(drug_name) {
  standardized_terminology %>%
    filter(grepl(drug_name, code_description, ignore.case = TRUE))
}

# Final combined result
combined_med_info <- data.frame()

# Loop through each drug class
for (class_name in names(drug_classes)) {
  
  # Get filtered codes for this class
  filtered_codes <- bind_rows(lapply(drug_classes[[class_name]], get_filtered_codes)) %>%
    distinct(code, .keep_all = TRUE)
  
  # Subset medication_ingredient_cohort
  subset <- medication_ingredient_cohort %>%
    inner_join(filtered_codes, by = "code") %>%
    select(patient_id, start_date, code)
  
  # Summarize to earliest and latest start dates
  summarized <- subset %>%
    group_by(patient_id, code) %>%
    summarise(
      earliest_start_date = min(start_date, na.rm = TRUE),
      latest_start_date = max(start_date, na.rm = TRUE),
      .groups = "drop"
    )
  
  # Join with pembro_initial
  joined <- summarized %>%
    inner_join(patient_cohort_flagged %>% select(patient_id, pembro_initiation, metformin), by = "patient_id") %>%
    mutate(
      other_diabetes_med = ifelse(
        !is.na(pembro_initiation) & pembro_initiation >= earliest_start_date & pembro_initiation <= latest_start_date, 1, 0
      ),
      med_class = class_name
    )
  
  # Append to full output
  combined_med_info <- bind_rows(combined_med_info, joined)
}

# HR

# helper to get HR, CI, p 
lincon_cox <- function(fit, L, label){
  b   <- coef(fit)
  V   <- vcov(fit)
  est <- as.numeric(L %*% b)
  se  <- sqrt(as.numeric(L %*% V %*% t(L)))
  z   <- est / se
  p   <- 2 * pnorm(-abs(z))
  tibble(
    stratum = label,
    logHR   = est,
    HR      = exp(est),
    CI_low  = exp(est - 1.96*se),
    CI_high = exp(est + 1.96*se),
    p_value = p
  )
}

# Find the coefficient names to build the right contrasts
coef_names <- names(coef(fit1))

make_contrast <- function(coef_names, ones) {
  v <- setNames(numeric(length(coef_names)), coef_names)
  v[intersect(names(v), ones)] <- 1
  matrix(v, nrow = 1)  
}

L_low  <- make_contrast(coef_names, ones = c("metformin_use"))

L_high <- make_contrast(coef_names, ones = c("metformin_use",
                                             "metformin_use:hba1c_group7%"))

lincon_cox <- function(fit, L, label){
  b   <- coef(fit)
  V   <- vcov(fit)
  est <- as.numeric(L %*% b)
  se  <- sqrt(as.numeric(L %*% V %*% t(L)))
  z   <- est / se
  p   <- 2 * pnorm(-abs(z))
  tibble::tibble(
    stratum = label,
    logHR   = est,
    HR      = exp(est),
    CI_low  = exp(est - 1.96*se),
    CI_high = exp(est + 1.96*se),
    p_value = p
  )
}

hr_table_interaction <- dplyr::bind_rows(
  lincon_cox(fit1, L_low,  label = "HbA1c < 7%"),
  lincon_cox(fit1, L_high, label = "HbA1c  7%")
) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    HR_CI = sprintf("%.2f (%.2f%.2f)", HR, CI_low, CI_high),
    p_fmt = ifelse(p_value < .001, "<0.001", sprintf("%.3f", p_value))
  ) %>%
  dplyr::select(stratum, HR, CI_low, CI_high, HR_CI, p_value, p_fmt)

  distinct(patient_id, code, .keep_all = TRUE)

Comparing 4 Categories of Metformin Use

metformin_years_at_pembro_tertile

# Step 1: Get tertile cutoffs (including max)
met_users <- patient_cohort_flagged %>% filter(metformin == 1)
tertile_cutoffs2 <- quantile(met_users$years_between_met_and_pembro, probs = seq(0, 1, 1/3), na.rm = TRUE)

# Step 2: Round cutoffs for readable labels
t1 <- round(tertile_cutoffs2[1], 1)
t2 <- round(tertile_cutoffs2[2], 1)
t3 <- round(tertile_cutoffs2[3], 1)
t4 <- ceiling(tertile_cutoffs2[4])  # This is the max

# Step 3: Create labeled and factored tertile variable
patient_cohort_flagged <- patient_cohort_flagged %>%
  mutate(
    metformin_years_at_pembro_tertile = case_when(
      metformin == 0 ~ "0",
      metformin == 1 & years_between_met_and_pembro <= t2 ~ paste0(t1, "", t2, " yrs"),
      metformin == 1 & years_between_met_and_pembro <= t3 ~ paste0(t2 + 0.01, "", t3, " yrs"),
      metformin == 1 & years_between_met_and_pembro <= t4 ~ paste0(t3 + 0.01, "", t4, " yrs"),
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    metformin_years_at_pembro_tertile = factor(
      metformin_years_at_pembro_tertile,
      levels = c(
        "0",
        paste0(t1, "", t2, " yrs"),
        paste0(t2 + 0.01, "", t3, " yrs"),
        paste0(t3 + 0.01, "", t4, " yrs")
      )
    )
  )
ggplot(
  data = patient_cohort_flagged %>% filter(metformin == 1),
  aes(x = metformin_years_at_pembro_tertile)
) +
  geom_bar(fill = "seagreen3", color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Metformin Users by Years on Metformin at Pembro Initiation (Tertiles)",
    x = "Years on Metformin (At Pembro Initiation)",
    y = "Number of Patients"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

surv_object <- Surv(time = patient_cohort_flagged$os_days, event = patient_cohort_flagged$death_event)

fit_km <- survfit(surv_object ~ metformin_years_at_pembro_tertile, data = patient_cohort_flagged)

Among metastatic patients (n = 253, events = 76), longer metformin use was significantly associated with improved overall survival (HR = 0.89, 95% CI: 0.791.00, p = 0.049), indicating that each additional year of metformin exposure reduced the hazard of death by approximately 11%. Radiation therapy was associated with higher mortality (HR = 1.94, p = 0.007), while the use of two or more other diabetes medication classes was linked to improved survival (HR = 0.21, p = 0.017).

In contrast, among non-metastatic patients (n = 230, events = 25), metformin duration showed no significant association with survival (HR = 0.99, 95% CI: 0.841.18, p = 0.96). However, the small number of events in this subgroup may have limited model stability, as indicated by convergence warnings.

Overall, these findings suggest that the survival benefit of longer metformin use is primarily observed in metastatic breast cancer patients, whereas its effect is minimal in non-metastatic cases.

Among metastatic patients (n = 253, 76 events), metformin use was marginally associated with improved overall survival (HR = 0.53, 95% CI: 0.281.00, p = 0.051). This suggests a potential protective trend, with metformin users experiencing approximately 47% lower hazard of death compared to non-users. Radiation therapy was linked to worse survival (HR = 1.89, p = 0.009), while the use of two or more other antidiabetic medication classes was associated with improved outcomes (HR = 0.22, p = 0.021).

In contrast, among non-metastatic patients (n = 230, 25 events), metformin use showed no significant survival association (HR = 1.77, 95% CI: 0.684.61, p = 0.24). Surgery remained a strong protective factor (HR = 0.17, p < 0.001), and older age at pembrolizumab initiation was associated with slightly higher risk (HR = 1.06, p = 0.013).

Overall, these results suggest that the potential survival benefit of metformin use is more evident in metastatic breast cancer patients, whereas its effect is minimal in the non-metastatic subgroup.
